							<img src="img/headshots/piehl.png" alt="Debra Piehl"/>
							<p>Debra  J. Piehl is the Analytical Specialist for Data-Driven Approaches to Crime and  Traffic Safety (DDACTS). In this role  she is responsible for all analysis aspects related to DDACTS workshops as well  as all follow-up technical assistance to agencies implementing DDACTS as an  analysis-driven, location-based operational model.</p>
							
  <p>Debra  served for over five years as the Compstat Director of the Massachusetts State  Police. While there she was responsible  for supporting analysis driven crime and crash reduction operations. She previously served the State Police as an  Intelligence Analyst Supervisor in the Commonwealth Fusion Center.</p>
<p>Prior  to joining the State Police, Debra served as Director of Planning &amp;  Research at the Newton Police Department. In addition to implementing Compstat and  analysis-driven operations at Newton, Debra also served as the CALEA  Accreditation Manager and was responsible for maintaining all updated policies  and procedures and for all grant administration. Debra serves on the National  Institute of Justice Operations Research Working Group and on the International  Association of Crime Analysts Ethics Committee. She is a regular speaker at the FBI Academy. She has extensive training in crime, crash and  intelligence analysis, police administration and incident database management. She holds a bachelor&rsquo;s degree in journalism  and political science and a master&rsquo;s degree in criminal justice. Debra is the past President of the  Massachusetts Association of Crime Analysts.</p>
<p>Debra  is the 2010 and 2003 recipient of the International Association of Crime  Analysts President&rsquo;s Award in recognition of her contributions to the crime  analysis profession.</p>
						</span>
